00:49:27,420 --> 00:49:29,420
Gauss's law tells us, among other things,

1008
00:49:29,420 --> 00:49:33,420
that the gravitational field of a spherically symmetric mass

1009
00:49:33,420 --> 00:49:38,420
only depends on the mass within the radius r

1010
00:49:38,420 --> 00:49:41,420
and doesn't depend at all on the mass outside the radius r.

1011
00:49:41,420 --> 00:49:44,420
A consequence of this, I think we talked about it last time,

1012
00:49:44,420 --> 00:49:46,420
but might as well just say it again,

1013
00:49:46,420 --> 00:49:51,420
is that if the mass was entirely distributed on a shell,

1014
00:49:51,420 --> 00:49:56,420
imagine the mass was on a shell, thin shell,

1015
00:49:56,420 --> 00:50:01,420
then inside the thin shell there would be no gravitational field at all.

1016
00:50:01,420 --> 00:50:05,420
Particles would move around as if there was no gravity at all.

1017
00:50:05,420 --> 00:50:08,420
On the other hand, particles outside the shell

1018
00:50:08,420 --> 00:50:11,420
would see the gravitational field of the shell exactly the same way.

1019
00:50:11,420 --> 00:50:14,420
The same as if it were a point at the center.

1020
00:50:14,420 --> 00:50:16,420
So that's a rather remarkable fact,

1021
00:50:16,420 --> 00:50:20,420
and it's special to the one over r squared law.

1022
00:50:20,420 --> 00:50:22,420
Notice that it tells you,

1023
00:50:22,420 --> 00:50:25,420
assuming Gauss's law and Gauss's theorem,

