And he will call the bottom, the floor of the elevator, he will call that x prime equals zero.

1318
01:06:38,500 --> 01:06:41,300
Prime means, in the frame of reference,

1319
01:06:41,300 --> 01:06:41,800
of the

1320
01:06:41,800 --> 01:06:42,100
of the

1321
01:06:42,120 --> 01:06:43,120
passenger.

1322
01:06:43,120 --> 01:06:45,120
Prime for passenger.

1323
01:06:45,120 --> 01:06:46,120
Okay?

1324
01:06:46,120 --> 01:06:48,120
So there's also an x prime coordinate.

1325
01:06:48,120 --> 01:06:52,120
Let's take x prime equals zero, that's the floor of the elevator.

1326
01:06:52,120 --> 01:06:57,120
The floor of the elevator is moving, and so the floor of the elevator looks like that.

1327
01:06:57,120 --> 01:07:02,120
As time goes on, the floor of the elevator moves further and further to the right.

1328
01:07:02,120 --> 01:07:10,120
Not only does the floor of the elevator, but x equals one follows along, and x equals two follow along.

1329
01:07:12,120 --> 01:07:16,120
Those are intended to be parallel, I'm not sure they are.

1330
01:07:16,120 --> 01:07:26,120
So the moving frame of reference measures distances relative to the floor of the elevator over here,

1331
01:07:26,120 --> 01:07:32,120
whereas the stationary frame of reference measures distances relative to x equals zero over here.

1332
01:07:32,120 --> 01:07:35,120
Now what's the relationship between x and x prime?

1333
01:07:35,120 --> 01:07:37,120
Well let's take any old point over here.

1334
01:07:37,120 --> 01:07:41,120
This is a point in space and time, it's a point of space at some time.

1335
01:07:41,120 --> 01:07:46,120
And let's ask what its x value is.

1336
01:07:46,120 --> 01:07:50,120
Its x value is the distance to here.

1337
01:07:50,120 --> 01:07:55,120
In other words, it's the coordinate that the stationary observer sees.

1338
01:07:55,120 --> 01:07:57,120
Just call it x.

1339
01:07:57,120 --> 01:07:59,120
What about x prime?

1340
01:07:59,120 --> 01:08:02,120
x prime is the distance to the floor of the elevator.

1341
01:08:02,120 --> 01:08:04,120
The elevator is moving.

1342
01:08:04,120 --> 01:08:09,120
So x prime is this distance.

1343
01:08:09,120 --> 01:08:11,120
What's the difference between them?

1344
01:08:11,120 --> 01:08:16,120
The difference between them is just the distance that the elevator has moved.

1345
01:08:16,120 --> 01:08:19,120
Velocity of the elevator times time.

1346
01:08:19,120 --> 01:08:23,120
That's how far the elevator has moved in an amount of time t.

1347
01:08:23,120 --> 01:08:28,120
It's moved with its velocity, it's moving with a uniform velocity, v times t.

1348
01:08:28,120 --> 01:08:29,120
So what is x prime?

1349
01:08:29,120 --> 01:08:32,120
Here's x prime over here.

1350
01:08:32,120 --> 01:08:37,120
x prime is equal to x minus vt.

1351
01:08:37,120 --> 01:08:41,120
That's the relationship between the primed coordinate,

1352
01:08:41,120 --> 01:08:43,120
and the unprimed coordinate.

1353
01:08:43,120 --> 01:08:47,120
And this you better get used to, this idea of relating frames of reference like this.

1354
01:08:47,120 --> 01:08:56,120
That's the relationship between the moving frame and the stationary frame.

1355
01:08:56,120 --> 01:08:59,120
Now there's one other thing in Newtonian physics.

1356
01:08:59,120 --> 01:09:01,120
We're not yet doing relativity.

1357
01:09:01,120 --> 01:09:06,120
In Newtonian physics, all observers measure the same time.

1358
01:09:06,120 --> 01:09:09,120
Time is the same for everybody.

1359
01:09:09,120 --> 01:09:14,120
And so we can write another equation that t prime is the same as t.

1360
01:09:14,120 --> 01:09:16,120
This is Newtonian physics.

1361
01:09:16,120 --> 01:09:19,120
This is not yet relativity, this is not yet Einstein.

1362
01:09:19,120 --> 01:09:21,120
It gets modified in Einstein.

1363
01:09:21,120 --> 01:09:28,120
But this is the relationship between the coordinates measured by the moving observer,

1364
01:09:28,120 --> 01:09:32,120
and the coordinates measured by the stationary observer.

1365
01:09:32,120 --> 01:09:34,120
It's a coordinate transformation.

1366
01:09:34,120 --> 01:09:37,120
x prime is x minus vt, t prime is equal to t.

1367
01:09:37,120 --> 01:09:49,120
Now, let's suppose now that there was an object which is standing still in the outside frame of reference.

1368
01:09:49,120 --> 01:09:51,120
This guy drops his ball here.

1369
01:09:51,120 --> 01:09:58,120
The ball stands, let's suppose it stands, let's say it stands still in my frame of reference, just for fun.

1370
01:09:58,120 --> 01:10:02,120
How does it move in his frame of reference?

1371
01:10:02,120 --> 01:10:07,120
If it's standing still in my frame of reference, what is it doing in his frame of reference?

1372
01:10:07,120 --> 01:10:11,120
I'm in particular interested in the velocity.

1373
01:10:11,120 --> 01:10:18,120
Alright, so if a ball is standing still in my frame of reference, it means x is equal to a constant.

1374
01:10:18,120 --> 01:10:20,120
It's just standing there still.

1375
01:10:20,120 --> 01:10:22,120
The elevator is going by.

1376
01:10:22,120 --> 01:10:26,120
The person in the elevator is looking at the ball, sees it moving.

1377
01:10:26,120 --> 01:10:31,120
Alright, if x is a constant, then x prime is of course just minus vt.

1378
01:10:31,120 --> 01:10:34,120
But what I want to do is differentiate this equation with respect to time.

1379
01:10:34,120 --> 01:10:36,120
What does it say?

1380
01:10:36,120 --> 01:10:41,120
It says that x prime dot, I'm using dot to indicate time derivative.

1381
01:10:41,120 --> 01:10:44,120
Standard notation, we've used it before.

1382
01:10:44,120 --> 01:10:49,120
A dot indicates a derivative with respect to time.

1383
01:10:49,120 --> 01:10:54,120
That's equal to x dot.

1384
01:10:54,120 --> 01:11:00,120
But if x is constant, if it's standing still in my frame of reference, that's zero.

1385
01:11:00,120 --> 01:11:05,120
What's the derivative of minus vt with respect to t?

1386
01:11:05,120 --> 01:11:07,120
Just minus v.

1387
01:11:07,120 --> 01:11:19,120
So this was a long-winded way to say that the velocity of the ball in the, as seen from inside the elevator, is minus v.

1388
01:11:19,120 --> 01:11:20,120
Of course it is.

1389
01:11:20,120 --> 01:11:23,120
The object was standing still in my frame of reference.

1390
01:11:23,120 --> 01:11:31,120
The observer is moving past it with velocity v, and of course sees it moving backward relative to him with velocity minus v.

1391
01:11:31,120 --> 01:11:33,120
That's all this says.

1392
01:11:33,120 --> 01:11:34,120
Okay.

1393
01:11:34,120 --> 01:11:40,120
So what does it say about the acceleration as seen in the moving frame of reference?

1394
01:11:40,120 --> 01:11:43,120
Let's differentiate it one more time.

1395
01:11:43,120 --> 01:11:49,120
Differentiating it one more time, that gives us the acceleration in the prime frame of reference.

1396
01:11:49,120 --> 01:11:52,120
What's the derivative of v with respect to t?

1397
01:11:52,120 --> 01:11:53,120
If v is constant?

1398
01:11:53,120 --> 01:11:55,120
Zero.

1399
01:11:55,120 --> 01:12:02,120
So if it's not accelerating in my frame of reference, it's not accelerating in his frame of reference.

1400
01:12:02,120 --> 01:12:03,120
Very simple.

1401
01:12:03,120 --> 01:12:04,120
Okay?

1402
01:12:04,120 --> 01:12:05,120
Trivial, in fact.

1403
01:12:05,120 --> 01:12:17,120
But now let's suppose that the elevator is not moving with uniform velocity, but that it's moving with uniform acceleration.

1404
01:12:17,120 --> 01:12:22,120
Then the distance that the elevator moves is not vt.

1405
01:12:22,120 --> 01:12:24,120
What is it?

1406
01:12:24,120 --> 01:12:32,120
Supposing it's moving with uniform acceleration, a-acceleration equals little g.

1407
01:12:32,120 --> 01:12:34,120
The acceleration due to gravity.

1408
01:12:34,120 --> 01:12:44,120
Then, how does the floor of the elevator move relative to me?

1409
01:12:44,120 --> 01:12:47,120
If it's accelerating like that.

1410
01:12:47,120 --> 01:12:51,120
Well, it doesn't move on a straight line, it moves on a curved line.

1411
01:12:51,120 --> 01:12:54,120
It moves on a parabola.

1412
01:12:54,120 --> 01:12:59,120
If it's uniformly accelerated relative to me, it's moving on a parabola.

1413
01:12:59,120 --> 01:13:06,120
And that parabola is x equals one half gt squared.

1414
01:13:06,120 --> 01:13:07,120
Is this known to everybody?

1415
01:13:07,120 --> 01:13:12,120
This is a standard formula for uniform acceleration.

1416
01:13:16,120 --> 01:13:18,120
Yell out if you don't know it.

1417
01:13:18,120 --> 01:13:25,120
Okay, this is the elementary calculation of a thing moving with uniform acceleration.

1418
01:13:25,120 --> 01:13:27,120
So, the moving observers, the floor, is x.

1419
01:13:27,120 --> 01:13:38,120
The moving observers, the floor, moves to the right, one half gt squared, along with the floor, all the other meter sticks.

1420
01:13:38,120 --> 01:13:40,120
The end of all the meter sticks do the same thing.

1421
01:13:40,120 --> 01:13:44,120
They accelerate off on a curved path in spacetime.

1422
01:13:44,120 --> 01:13:48,120
An acceleration means a curved path in spacetime.

1423
01:13:48,120 --> 01:13:53,120
So, let's see what the relation between x prime and x is.

1424
01:13:53,120 --> 01:13:55,120
Again, same thing.

1425
01:13:55,120 --> 01:13:56,120
Here's x prime.

1426
01:13:56,120 --> 01:13:58,120
Here's x.

1427
01:13:58,120 --> 01:14:00,120
What's the difference between them?

1428
01:14:00,120 --> 01:14:06,120
The difference between them is x minus one half gt squared.

1429
01:14:06,120 --> 01:14:11,120
This distance is one half gt squared.

1430
01:14:11,120 --> 01:14:15,120
The distance from here to here.

1431
01:14:15,120 --> 01:14:20,120
x prime is x minus gt squared.

1432
01:14:20,120 --> 01:14:22,120
This is the neutral equation.

1433
01:14:22,120 --> 01:14:24,120
This is the neutral equation.

1434
01:14:24,120 --> 01:14:25,120
This is the neutral equation.

1435
01:14:25,120 --> 01:14:31,120
This is the new transformation for transforming to an accelerated frame of reference.

1436
01:14:31,120 --> 01:14:41,120
Okay, let's say again that the passenger drops a coin, or whatever it is, and that the coin happens to be standing still.

1437
01:14:41,120 --> 01:14:46,120
He throws it in just such a way that it's standing still in my frame of reference.

1438
01:14:46,120 --> 01:14:49,120
That again means x is a constant.

1439
01:14:49,120 --> 01:14:51,120
What does it say about x prime?

1440
01:14:51,120 --> 01:14:53,120
It says that x prime...

1441
01:14:53,120 --> 01:14:55,120
Well, let's work it out.

1442
01:14:55,120 --> 01:14:57,120
Let's work it out.

1443
01:14:57,120 --> 01:15:01,120
What does it say about the velocity?

1444
01:15:01,120 --> 01:15:10,120
If x is standing still, and we differentiate this, we get the velocity in the prime frame of reference.

1445
01:15:10,120 --> 01:15:14,120
Zero from differentiating x, standing still in my frame of reference.

1446
01:15:14,120 --> 01:15:20,120
But what happens if we differentiate minus one half gt squared?

1447
01:15:20,120 --> 01:15:21,120
Minus gt.

1448
01:15:21,120 --> 01:15:30,120
But I'm interested in the acceleration that the observer in here sees, so I differentiate it again.

1449
01:15:30,120 --> 01:15:32,120
x prime double dot.

1450
01:15:32,120 --> 01:15:36,120
The acceleration seen from inside here.

1451
01:15:36,120 --> 01:15:39,120
What do I get when I differentiate it once more?

1452
01:15:39,120 --> 01:15:42,120
Just minus g.

1453
01:15:42,120 --> 01:15:49,120
This is a mathematical statement of the simple trivial observation

1454
01:15:49,120 --> 01:15:53,120
that acceleration works the same way as gravity.

1455
01:15:53,120 --> 01:15:58,120
The accelerated elevator gives rise to an acceleration for anything that you drop,

1456
01:15:58,120 --> 01:16:00,120
which is just minus g.

1457
01:16:00,120 --> 01:16:04,120
Just like in an ordinary gravitational field of the Earth.

1458
01:16:04,120 --> 01:16:12,120
So anything which is dropped in this elevator accelerates toward the floor.

1459
01:16:12,120 --> 01:16:16,120
Not in the direction of the elevator's acceleration,

1460
01:16:16,120 --> 01:16:18,120
but in the backward direction.

1461
01:16:18,120 --> 01:16:20,120
That's the minus sign here.

1462
01:16:20,120 --> 01:16:25,120
And it accelerates backward with the acceleration minus g.

1463
01:16:25,120 --> 01:16:28,120
So that's a mathematical statement.

1464
01:16:28,120 --> 01:16:35,120
But what I wanted to bring out is that it really has to do with using a set of curved coordinates.

1465
01:16:35,120 --> 01:16:45,120
It has to do, or that acceleration is really the choice of a curvy linear set of coordinates to describe space-time.

1466
01:16:45,120 --> 01:16:47,120
That's the real lesson here.

1467
01:16:47,120 --> 01:16:49,120
Acceleration.

1468
01:16:49,120 --> 01:16:58,120
An accelerated reference frame is described by a coordinate transformation to a set of curved coordinates.

1469
01:16:58,120 --> 01:17:00,120
We need to keep that in mind.

1470
01:17:00,120 --> 01:17:05,120
The connection between gravity and curvature will be beginning to develop.

1471
01:17:05,120 --> 01:17:09,120
But having done that, let's now come back to some simple physics.

1472
01:17:09,120 --> 01:17:15,120
One of the things that Einstein became instantly famous for.

1473
01:17:17,120 --> 01:17:20,120
We can work it out qualitatively.

1474
01:17:20,120 --> 01:17:22,120
It's the bending of light.

1475
01:17:22,120 --> 01:17:27,120
Okay, so his first step was to say,

1476
01:17:27,120 --> 01:17:31,120
I really mean it when I say that the laws of physics in a gravitational field

1477
01:17:31,120 --> 01:17:36,120
are the same as the laws of physics in an accelerated reference frame.

1478
01:17:36,120 --> 01:17:41,120
And in particular, not just the laws of Newtonian mechanics, but the laws of everything.

1479
01:17:41,120 --> 01:17:46,120
Nobody at that time had the faintest idea how gravity affects electric energy.

1480
01:17:46,120 --> 01:17:49,120
How gravity affects electric and magnetic fields.

1481
01:17:49,120 --> 01:17:51,120
They didn't know.

1482
01:17:51,120 --> 01:17:57,120
In fact, I don't even know that the question was asked at that time in a serious way.

1483
01:17:57,120 --> 01:18:03,120
And so it wasn't known, for that reason it wasn't known how gravity affects the motion of light rays.

1484
01:18:03,120 --> 01:18:08,120
What Einstein said is, I now know how gravity should affect the motion of light rays.

1485
01:18:08,120 --> 01:18:09,120
So here's his elevator.

1486
01:18:09,120 --> 01:18:11,120
Now I'm drawing the elevator vertical.

1487
01:18:11,120 --> 01:18:14,120
The vertical, the elevator will accelerate upward.

1488
01:18:14,120 --> 01:18:16,120
And let's suppose a light beam is moving.

1489
01:18:16,120 --> 01:18:20,120
And the light beam is shined from one side to the other.

1490
01:18:20,120 --> 01:18:23,120
First, suppose the elevator is not accelerating.

1491
01:18:23,120 --> 01:18:27,120
Let's suppose the elevator is standing still.

1492
01:18:27,120 --> 01:18:29,120
And you shine a light beam, what does it do?

1493
01:18:29,120 --> 01:18:32,120
It goes in a straight line, and it goes right across the elevator.

1494
01:18:32,120 --> 01:18:34,120
It hits this point over here.

1495
01:18:34,120 --> 01:18:37,120
Now what happens if the elevator is accelerated upward?

1496
01:18:37,120 --> 01:18:40,120
Well, let's send the light beam, just arbitrarily,

1497
01:18:40,120 --> 01:18:46,120
let's send the light beam at exactly the instant when the elevator begins to accelerate.

1498
01:18:46,120 --> 01:18:50,120
It's not yet moving, it's just beginning to accelerate.

1499
01:18:50,120 --> 01:18:53,120
So the light beam starts moving off horizontally.

1500
01:18:53,120 --> 01:18:55,120
But now the accelerate,

1501
01:18:55,120 --> 01:18:56,120
I keep saying accelerate,

1502
01:18:56,120 --> 01:18:59,120
the elevator is accelerating upward.

1503
01:18:59,120 --> 01:19:03,120
And so where does the light beam hit the other side of the elevator?

1504
01:19:03,120 --> 01:19:05,120
Down here somewheres.

1505
01:19:05,120 --> 01:19:07,120
And it travels in a curved path.

1506
01:19:07,120 --> 01:19:12,120
In fact, that curved path will be a parabola again.

1507
01:19:12,120 --> 01:19:15,120
It will travel on a parabolic orbit.

1508
01:19:16,120 --> 01:19:20,120
And that parabolic orbit,

1509
01:19:20,120 --> 01:19:23,120
you can work out easily,

1510
01:19:23,120 --> 01:19:26,120
just from the motion of the elevator.

1511
01:19:26,120 --> 01:19:29,120
And what do you find?

1512
01:19:29,120 --> 01:19:35,120
You find that the light ray has a downward component of acceleration,

1513
01:19:35,120 --> 01:19:37,120
which is equal to g.

1514
01:19:37,120 --> 01:19:39,120
The same acceleration.

1515
01:19:39,120 --> 01:19:43,120
If the elevator is accelerated upward,

1516
01:19:43,120 --> 01:19:45,120
with acceleration g,

1517
01:19:45,120 --> 01:19:50,120
then the light ray will have a downward component of acceleration,

1518
01:19:50,120 --> 01:19:53,120
which will also be g.

1519
01:19:53,120 --> 01:19:56,120
So by that little argument,

1520
01:19:56,120 --> 01:19:58,120
nothing more than that,

1521
01:19:58,120 --> 01:20:03,120
Einstein deduced the fact that light falls in a gravitational field.

1522
01:20:03,120 --> 01:20:06,120
As I said, this was unknown.

1523
01:20:06,120 --> 01:20:08,120
Nobody even suspected it,

1524
01:20:08,120 --> 01:20:11,120
that the existence of heavy masses,

1525
01:20:11,120 --> 01:20:13,120
which create gravitational fields,

1526
01:20:13,120 --> 01:20:14,120
would cause

1527
01:20:14,120 --> 01:20:18,120
light to do anything other than travel in a straight line.

1528
01:20:18,120 --> 01:20:21,120
In fact, light doesn't travel in a straight line

1529
01:20:21,120 --> 01:20:24,120
when it passes through the Earth,

1530
01:20:24,120 --> 01:20:26,120
passes across the Earth.

1531
01:20:26,120 --> 01:20:27,120
Why?

1532
01:20:27,120 --> 01:20:30,120
Because the gravitational field of the Earth can be thought of

1533
01:20:30,120 --> 01:20:32,120
as an upward acceleration.

1534
01:20:32,120 --> 01:20:34,120
And so, light will fall.

1535
01:20:34,120 --> 01:20:36,120
Let's go through...

1536
01:20:36,120 --> 01:20:37,120
Question?

1537
01:20:37,120 --> 01:20:38,120
Yeah.

1538
01:20:38,120 --> 01:20:41,120
Suppose you shine the light in the direction of the acceleration.

1539
01:20:41,120 --> 01:20:42,120
Yeah.

1540
01:20:42,120 --> 01:20:43,120
It's a little more complicated.

1541
01:20:43,120 --> 01:20:46,120
It still has an effect,

1542
01:20:46,120 --> 01:20:48,120
and it affects the energy of the light ray.

1543
01:20:48,120 --> 01:20:50,120
But it won't affect the speed.

1544
01:20:50,120 --> 01:20:51,120
No.

1545
01:20:51,120 --> 01:20:52,120
Because that depends on...

1546
01:20:52,120 --> 01:20:53,120
Right.

1547
01:20:53,120 --> 01:20:55,120
The acceleration in the vertical direction

1548
01:20:55,120 --> 01:20:58,120
will correspond to change in energy of the...

1549
01:20:58,120 --> 01:20:59,120
Yeah.

1550
01:20:59,120 --> 01:21:00,120
It won't affect the speed.

1551
01:21:00,120 --> 01:21:01,120
That's correct.

1552
01:21:01,120 --> 01:21:02,120
One more question.

1553
01:21:02,120 --> 01:21:03,120
Yeah.

1554
01:21:03,120 --> 01:21:05,120
The Eddington experiment that verified general relativity.

1555
01:21:05,120 --> 01:21:06,120
Yeah.

1556
01:21:06,120 --> 01:21:08,120
If you take plain old Newtonian mechanics

1557
01:21:08,120 --> 01:21:11,120
and assume that a photon is a particle of mass,

1558
01:21:11,120 --> 01:21:12,120
E over C squared,

1559
01:21:12,120 --> 01:21:15,120
and just use Newton's gravity equation,

1560
01:21:15,120 --> 01:21:16,120
will it properly...

1561
01:21:16,120 --> 01:21:17,120
Yeah. Let's do it.

1562
01:21:17,120 --> 01:21:18,120
Let's do it.

1563
01:21:18,120 --> 01:21:19,120
Let's do it.

1564
01:21:19,120 --> 01:21:20,120
And that's what it...

1565
01:21:20,120 --> 01:21:22,120
That's general relativity predicts exactly the same thing.

1566
01:21:22,120 --> 01:21:25,120
By a factor of two.

1567
01:21:25,120 --> 01:21:29,120
But let's see if we can roughly work out

1568
01:21:29,120 --> 01:21:32,120
the bending of light by the sun.

1569
01:21:32,120 --> 01:21:33,120
Okay.

1570
01:21:33,120 --> 01:21:34,120
The question is this.

1571
01:21:34,120 --> 01:21:39,120
If a light ray passes the sun,

1572
01:21:39,120 --> 01:21:40,120
and clearly,

1573
01:21:40,120 --> 01:21:42,120
Einstein has already proved that light rays

1574
01:21:42,120 --> 01:21:43,120
are not the same as light rays.

1575
01:21:43,120 --> 01:21:44,120
So,

1576
01:21:44,120 --> 01:21:45,120
if a light ray passes the sun,

1577
01:21:45,120 --> 01:21:46,120
and the sun falls in a gravitational field,

1578
01:21:46,120 --> 01:21:47,120
so he wanted to estimate...

1579
01:21:47,120 --> 01:21:48,120
The first thing he did

1580
01:21:48,120 --> 01:21:49,120
before he had the full apparatus

1581
01:21:49,120 --> 01:21:50,120
of the general theory of relativity,

1582
01:21:50,120 --> 01:21:51,120
he had as much as I've explained up till now,

1583
01:21:51,120 --> 01:21:52,120
and he said,

1584
01:21:52,120 --> 01:21:53,120
I will try to estimate

1585
01:21:53,120 --> 01:21:54,120
how much the light bends.

1586
01:21:54,120 --> 01:21:55,120
In other words,

1587
01:21:55,120 --> 01:21:56,120
what angle does the light ray get accelerated...

1588
01:21:56,120 --> 01:21:57,120
What's the right word?

1589
01:21:57,120 --> 01:21:58,120
Deflected.

1590
01:21:58,120 --> 01:21:59,120
Yeah.

1591
01:21:59,120 --> 01:22:00,120
By what angle does the light ray get deflected?

1592
01:22:00,120 --> 01:22:01,120
All right.

1593
01:22:01,120 --> 01:22:02,120
We can make an estimate.

1594
01:22:02,120 --> 01:22:03,120
Now,

1595
01:22:03,120 --> 01:22:04,120
at the end of the day,

1596
01:22:04,120 --> 01:22:05,120
we can make an estimate

1597
01:22:05,120 --> 01:22:06,120
of the light ray's speed.

1598
01:22:06,120 --> 01:22:07,120
So,

1599
01:22:07,120 --> 01:22:08,120
if the light ray is...

1600
01:22:08,120 --> 01:22:09,120
If the light ray is...

1601
01:22:09,120 --> 01:22:10,120
If the light ray is...

1602
01:22:10,120 --> 01:22:11,120
All right.

1603
01:22:11,120 --> 01:22:12,120
We can make an estimate.

1604
01:22:12,120 --> 01:22:13,120
Now,

1605
01:22:13,120 --> 01:22:14,120
at this point,

1606
01:22:14,120 --> 01:22:15,120
he was reduced to estimates

1607
01:22:15,120 --> 01:22:17,120
because he didn't know the details

1608
01:22:17,120 --> 01:22:19,120
of how the spherical Earth

1609
01:22:19,120 --> 01:22:21,120
with its varying gravitational field

1610
01:22:21,120 --> 01:22:22,120
would really affect things.

1611
01:22:22,120 --> 01:22:23,120
But, in particular,

1612
01:22:23,120 --> 01:22:24,120
he was interested in a light ray

1613
01:22:24,120 --> 01:22:27,120
which just skimmed the surface of the sun,

1614
01:22:27,120 --> 01:22:29,120
got as close to the sun as...

1615
01:22:29,120 --> 01:22:30,120
Why?

1616
01:22:30,120 --> 01:22:32,120
Because the effect would be maximal

1617
01:22:32,120 --> 01:22:34,120
the closer the light ray got to the sun.

1618
01:22:34,120 --> 01:22:35,120
Of course,

1619
01:22:35,120 --> 01:22:36,120
he wasn't interested in light rays

1620
01:22:36,120 --> 01:22:37,120
that went through the sun.

1621
01:22:37,120 --> 01:22:38,120
Light rays don't go through the sun.

1622
01:22:38,120 --> 01:22:40,120
A light ray that just skimmed

1623
01:22:40,120 --> 01:22:41,120
the sun,

1624
01:22:41,120 --> 01:22:43,120
how much it got deflected.

1625
01:22:43,120 --> 01:22:44,120
Okay,

1626
01:22:44,120 --> 01:22:46,120
let's see if we can figure it out.

1627
01:22:52,120 --> 01:22:53,120
First of all,

1628
01:22:53,120 --> 01:22:55,120
in passing...

1629
01:22:55,120 --> 01:22:58,120
In passing through the...

1630
01:22:58,120 --> 01:23:01,120
When it passes close to the sun,

1631
01:23:01,120 --> 01:23:03,120
when it passes close to the sun,

1632
01:23:03,120 --> 01:23:06,120
it has an acceleration toward the sun,

1633
01:23:06,120 --> 01:23:08,120
which is just the acceleration field

1634
01:23:08,120 --> 01:23:09,120
of the sun.

1635
01:23:09,120 --> 01:23:10,120
So, when it passes

1636
01:23:10,120 --> 01:23:11,120
close to the sun,

1637
01:23:11,120 --> 01:23:12,120
it's in the vicinity of the sun.

1638
01:23:12,120 --> 01:23:13,120
Let's break it up.

1639
01:23:13,120 --> 01:23:16,120
When it's out beyond the distance

1640
01:23:16,120 --> 01:23:18,120
comparable to the radius of the sun,

1641
01:23:18,120 --> 01:23:21,120
it's too far from the sun to feel anything.

1642
01:23:21,120 --> 01:23:23,120
When it's within some region

1643
01:23:23,120 --> 01:23:26,120
comparable to twice the radius of the sun here,

1644
01:23:26,120 --> 01:23:29,120
it feels the gravitational pull of the sun.

1645
01:23:29,120 --> 01:23:33,120
What's the acceleration that it feels downward?

1646
01:23:33,120 --> 01:23:34,120
Well, for that,

1647
01:23:34,120 --> 01:23:35,120
we just have to work out

1648
01:23:35,120 --> 01:23:37,120
the acceleration due to gravity.

1649
01:23:37,120 --> 01:23:38,120
What we have to work out

1650
01:23:38,120 --> 01:23:39,120
is how much acceleration

1651
01:23:39,120 --> 01:23:41,120
is there at the surface of the sun.

1652
01:23:41,120 --> 01:23:43,120
I think we already had a formula for that, right?

1653
01:23:43,120 --> 01:23:47,120
The acceleration due is

1654
01:23:47,120 --> 01:23:50,120
m, mass of the sun,

1655
01:23:50,120 --> 01:23:53,120
g over r squared.

1656
01:23:55,120 --> 01:23:57,120
That's the...

1657
01:23:57,120 --> 01:23:59,120
Do I have that right?

1658
01:23:59,120 --> 01:24:04,120
mg over r squared downward, right?

1659
01:24:04,120 --> 01:24:06,120
Everything gets accelerated downward,

1660
01:24:06,120 --> 01:24:08,120
light as well as everything,

1661
01:24:08,120 --> 01:24:10,120
and all with the same acceleration.

1662
01:24:10,120 --> 01:24:13,120
So mg divided by r squared

1663
01:24:13,120 --> 01:24:14,120
is the acceleration,

1664
01:24:14,120 --> 01:24:17,120
the vertical component of the acceleration.

1665
01:24:17,120 --> 01:24:19,120
All right?

1666
01:24:19,120 --> 01:24:22,120
How much velocity does the...

1667
01:24:22,120 --> 01:24:25,120
How much vertical component of the velocity...

1668
01:24:25,120 --> 01:24:27,120
Now, vertical doesn't mean toward the sun.

1669
01:24:27,120 --> 01:24:29,120
It means vertical on the blackboard here.

1670
01:24:29,120 --> 01:24:31,120
How much vertical component of velocity

1671
01:24:31,120 --> 01:24:35,120
does it have after it passes the sun?

1672
01:24:35,120 --> 01:24:38,120
Well, to calculate the change in velocity

1673
01:24:38,120 --> 01:24:41,120
you multiply the acceleration by time.

1674
01:24:41,120 --> 01:24:43,120
Acceleration times time

1675
01:24:43,120 --> 01:24:45,120
is the change in velocity.

1676
01:24:45,120 --> 01:24:47,120
So you take this acceleration

1677
01:24:47,120 --> 01:24:50,120
and multiply it by the amount of time,

1678
01:24:50,120 --> 01:24:54,120
let's call it delta t,

1679
01:24:54,120 --> 01:24:58,120
that it takes for the light beam

1680
01:24:58,120 --> 01:25:02,120
to cross across the radius of the sun.

1681
01:25:02,120 --> 01:25:04,120
Now, we can estimate that

1682
01:25:04,120 --> 01:25:06,120
because we know how fast light moves.

1683
01:25:06,120 --> 01:25:08,120
It moves with the speed of light.

1684
01:25:08,120 --> 01:25:13,120
So how long does it take?

1685
01:25:13,120 --> 01:25:15,120
It takes a time, delta t,

1686
01:25:15,120 --> 01:25:18,120
which is approximately twice the rate...

1687
01:25:18,120 --> 01:25:19,120
this distance here,

1688
01:25:19,120 --> 01:25:21,120
divided by the velocity.

1689
01:25:21,120 --> 01:25:25,120
That's velocity times time equals distance.

1690
01:25:25,120 --> 01:25:28,120
So time is distance that it travels

1691
01:25:28,120 --> 01:25:30,120
divided by the velocity.

1692
01:25:30,120 --> 01:25:31,120
But what velocity?

1693
01:25:31,120 --> 01:25:33,120
The velocity of light.

1694
01:25:33,120 --> 01:25:35,120
The velocity of light going across here.

1695
01:25:35,120 --> 01:25:38,120
So that's 2r divided by c.

1696
01:25:38,120 --> 01:25:43,120
So let's plug that in.

1697
01:25:43,120 --> 01:25:45,120
That gives us another 2.

1698
01:25:45,120 --> 01:25:52,120
2 is not important.

1699
01:25:52,120 --> 01:25:56,120
r divided by c.

1700
01:25:56,120 --> 01:25:58,120
And what is that?

1701
01:25:58,120 --> 01:26:03,120
That's twice mg over rc.

1702
01:26:03,120 --> 01:26:07,120
That's the downward component

1703
01:26:07,120 --> 01:26:09,120
of velocity here.

1704
01:26:09,120 --> 01:26:11,120
But that's not the angle.

1705
01:26:11,120 --> 01:26:14,120
The angle is basically the ratio of...

1706
01:26:14,120 --> 01:26:17,120
If we have a small angle relative to the horizontal...

1707
01:26:17,120 --> 01:26:19,120
Here's the horizontal.

1708
01:26:19,120 --> 01:26:21,120
Small angle relative to the horizontal.

1709
01:26:21,120 --> 01:26:23,120
That's the velocity.

1710
01:26:23,120 --> 01:26:25,120
This is the direction of the velocity

1711
01:26:25,120 --> 01:26:27,120
after it passes the sun.

1712
01:26:27,120 --> 01:26:29,120
Then the downward component here,

1713
01:26:29,120 --> 01:26:32,120
the angle is the ratio of the downward component

1714
01:26:32,120 --> 01:26:34,120
to the horizontal component.

1715
01:26:34,120 --> 01:26:37,120
The downward component divided by the velocity

1716
01:26:37,120 --> 01:26:39,120
divided by the horizontal component

1717
01:26:39,120 --> 01:26:42,120
is essentially the angle,

1718
01:26:42,120 --> 01:26:45,120
at least if the angle is small.

1719
01:26:45,120 --> 01:26:47,120
So the angle,

1720
01:26:47,120 --> 01:26:49,120
let's call it theta,

1721
01:26:49,120 --> 01:26:52,120
is equal to the ratio of the downward component,

1722
01:26:52,120 --> 01:26:53,120
here it is,

1723
01:26:53,120 --> 01:26:58,120
2mg over rc.

1724
01:26:58,120 --> 01:27:00,120
That's the downward component of the velocity.

1725
01:27:00,120 --> 01:27:05,120
Divide that by the horizontal component of the velocity,

1726
01:27:05,120 --> 01:27:07,120
and that gives you the angle.

1727
01:27:07,120 --> 01:27:10,120
Another horizontal component of the velocity

1728
01:27:10,120 --> 01:27:11,120
is 1 over c,

1729
01:27:11,120 --> 01:27:13,120
and here's the answer.

1730
01:27:13,120 --> 01:27:19,120
2mg over rc squared.

1731
01:27:19,120 --> 01:27:22,120
That's a very small angle typically,

1732
01:27:22,120 --> 01:27:25,120
mainly because c is a big number

1733
01:27:25,120 --> 01:27:27,120
and g is a small number.

1734
01:27:27,120 --> 01:27:29,120
So g is a very small number,

1735
01:27:29,120 --> 01:27:31,120
c is a very big number,

1736
01:27:31,120 --> 01:27:33,120
c squared is even bigger,

1737
01:27:33,120 --> 01:27:36,120
and so that's typically a small angle

1738
01:27:36,120 --> 01:27:39,120
when the light ray goes across the sun.

1739
01:27:41,120 --> 01:27:44,120
So that was the crude estimate

1740
01:27:44,120 --> 01:27:46,120
that Einstein made.

1741
01:27:46,120 --> 01:27:50,120
I can't remember what the correct answer is

1742
01:27:50,120 --> 01:27:52,120
from the general theory of relativity.

1743
01:27:52,120 --> 01:27:54,120
It's within a factor of two of this.

1744
01:27:54,120 --> 01:27:56,120
I think maybe it's just exactly

1745
01:27:56,120 --> 01:27:57,120
either twice this or half of it,

1746
01:27:57,120 --> 01:27:59,120
I can't remember.

1747
01:28:01,120 --> 01:28:03,120
And so every light beam

1748
01:28:03,120 --> 01:28:07,120
that passes by the edge of the sun

1749
01:28:07,120 --> 01:28:09,120
gets deflected by that much.

1750
01:28:09,120 --> 01:28:12,120
That was Einstein's prediction.

1751
01:28:12,120 --> 01:28:15,120
It was verified by looking at stars

1752
01:28:15,120 --> 01:28:18,120
passing across the sun during an eclipse.

1753
01:28:18,120 --> 01:28:20,120
We don't need to go through that.

1754
01:28:20,120 --> 01:28:22,120
Most of you know the story.

1755
01:28:24,120 --> 01:28:26,120
But the main point here

1756
01:28:26,120 --> 01:28:30,120
is that Einstein used the idea

1757
01:28:30,120 --> 01:28:32,120
that gravity and acceleration are the same.

1758
01:28:32,120 --> 01:28:35,120
Something that was known to everybody,

1759
01:28:35,120 --> 01:28:37,120
but he used it in a context

1760
01:28:37,120 --> 01:28:39,120
which nobody had ever thought of.

1761
01:28:39,120 --> 01:28:41,120
Namely, he applied it to the motion of light

1762
01:28:41,120 --> 01:28:44,120
and to electromagnetic phenomena in general.

1763
01:28:44,120 --> 01:28:47,120
Okay, so that's...

1764
01:28:47,120 --> 01:28:50,120
Now...

1765
01:28:50,120 --> 01:28:54,120
Yes, gravity is like acceleration,

1766
01:28:54,120 --> 01:28:58,120
but that idea is pretty much limited

1767
01:28:58,120 --> 01:29:00,120
to a uniform gravitational field,

1768
01:29:00,120 --> 01:29:02,120
a uniform vector,

1769
01:29:02,120 --> 01:29:04,120
a vertical gravitational field.

1770
01:29:04,120 --> 01:29:06,120
It doesn't really make sense

1771
01:29:06,120 --> 01:29:08,120
when you try to think about it globally

1772
01:29:08,120 --> 01:29:11,120
in terms of the Earth's gravitational field

1773
01:29:11,120 --> 01:29:14,120
when you stop thinking of a flat Earth approximation.

1774
01:29:14,120 --> 01:29:16,120
So here's the Earth.

1775
01:29:20,120 --> 01:29:24,120
The effect of the Earth's gravity

1776
01:29:24,120 --> 01:29:27,120
on anything over here, out here,

1777
01:29:27,120 --> 01:29:29,120
Einstein said is exactly the same

1778
01:29:29,120 --> 01:29:31,120
as if you were in an elevator over here,

1779
01:29:31,120 --> 01:29:37,120
accelerating upward with a certain acceleration.

1780
01:29:37,120 --> 01:29:40,120
Well, first of all,

1781
01:29:40,120 --> 01:29:42,120
you can...

1782
01:29:42,120 --> 01:29:44,120
The acceleration has to be different

1783
01:29:44,120 --> 01:29:46,120
in different places,

1784
01:29:46,120 --> 01:29:48,120
different direction in different places,

1785
01:29:48,120 --> 01:29:51,120
different magnitude in different places.

1786
01:29:51,120 --> 01:29:54,120
And so there's no overall sense

1787
01:29:54,120 --> 01:29:56,120
in which you can take the gravitational field

1788
01:29:56,120 --> 01:29:58,120
of the Earth and replace it

1789
01:29:58,120 --> 01:30:01,120
by a single accelerated frame of reference.

1790
01:30:01,120 --> 01:30:04,120
The acceleration has to be this way over here,

1791
01:30:04,120 --> 01:30:06,120
this way over here,

1792
01:30:06,120 --> 01:30:07,120
this way over here,

1793
01:30:07,120 --> 01:30:08,120
this way over here.

1794
01:30:08,120 --> 01:30:10,120
So there's certainly no sense

1795
01:30:10,120 --> 01:30:13,120
in which the full gravitational field of the Earth

1796
01:30:13,120 --> 01:30:16,120
can be replaced by saying

1797
01:30:16,120 --> 01:30:20,120
you're in an accelerated reference frame.

1798
01:30:20,120 --> 01:30:25,120
What you can say is for a small amount of time

1799
01:30:25,120 --> 01:30:28,120
and over a small amount of distance,

1800
01:30:28,120 --> 01:30:30,120
distances which are too small

1801
01:30:30,120 --> 01:30:33,120
to detect the fact that the gravitational field

1802
01:30:33,120 --> 01:30:36,120
has different directions in different places,

1803
01:30:36,120 --> 01:30:38,120
in other words, on a small elevator,

1804
01:30:38,120 --> 01:30:42,120
for a small amount of time,

1805
01:30:42,120 --> 01:30:45,120
the effect of the Earth's gravitational field

1806
01:30:45,120 --> 01:30:48,120
is the same as the effect of an accelerated elevator,

1807
01:30:48,120 --> 01:30:50,120
but only for a small amount of time.

1808
01:30:50,120 --> 01:30:51,120
Why?

1809
01:30:51,120 --> 01:30:54,120
Because, well, unless you allow the acceleration

1810
01:30:54,120 --> 01:30:55,120
to change with time,

1811
01:30:55,120 --> 01:30:57,120
but for a small amount of time,

1812
01:30:57,120 --> 01:30:59,120
you can pretend that a small amount of time

1813
01:30:59,120 --> 01:31:01,120
and a small amount of space,

1814
01:31:01,120 --> 01:31:03,120
not enough space to feel the change

1815
01:31:03,120 --> 01:31:05,120
in the direction of gravity,

1816
01:31:05,120 --> 01:31:08,120
you can say that gravity has the same effect

1817
01:31:08,120 --> 01:31:10,120
as acceleration.

1818
01:31:10,120 --> 01:31:11,120
But if you really think about it,

1819
01:31:11,120 --> 01:31:13,120
I mean, you have to think much more deeply

1820
01:31:13,120 --> 01:31:16,120
about what the gravitational field

1821
01:31:16,120 --> 01:31:18,120
of the whole round Earth is.

1822
01:31:18,120 --> 01:31:21,120
Now, this is related to something else.

1823
01:31:21,120 --> 01:31:25,120
If you're freely falling near the surface of the Earth,

1824
01:31:25,120 --> 01:31:28,120
you don't feel the effect of gravity.

1825
01:31:29,120 --> 01:31:31,120
You feel, you can tell the difference

1826
01:31:31,120 --> 01:31:33,120
between free fall and not free fall,

1827
01:31:33,120 --> 01:31:35,120
but there's no difference between falling

1828
01:31:35,120 --> 01:31:37,120
at the surface of the Earth

1829
01:31:37,120 --> 01:31:40,120
and being out in the middle of space

1830
01:31:40,120 --> 01:31:42,120
with no gravitating objects at all.

1831
01:31:42,120 --> 01:31:46,120
What about,

1832
01:31:46,120 --> 01:31:50,120
what about somebody falling over here?

1833
01:31:50,120 --> 01:31:53,120
Can somebody falling over here,

1834
01:31:53,120 --> 01:31:54,120
just in free fall,

1835
01:31:54,120 --> 01:31:57,120
can they or can they not tell

1836
01:31:57,120 --> 01:31:59,120
the difference between

1837
01:31:59,120 --> 01:32:01,120
falling and being in an elevator,

1838
01:32:01,120 --> 01:32:02,120
so to speak,

1839
01:32:02,120 --> 01:32:04,120
